statement.p:
Do the indicated vector operation, if it is defined.


\vec{2 1 1} + \vec{3 0 4}

5 \vec{4 -1}

\vec{1 5 1} - \vec{3 1 1}

7 \vec{2 1} + 9 \vec{3 5}

\vec{1 2} + \vec{1 2 3}

6 \vec{3 1 1}  - 4 \vec{2 0 3} + 2 \vec{1 1 5}

Consider the following picture of two vectors v, w:

					\begin{tikzpicture}[scale=1,
					every label/.style={fill=none,inner sep=1pt,font=\small},
					whitebg/.style={fill=white}]
					\path[clip] (-3.2,-3.2) rectangle (3.2, 3.2);
					\draw[very thin, gray, dotted] (-3.2, 0) -- (3.2, 0)
					(0, -3.2) -- (0, 3.2);
					\begin{scope}
					\pgftransformcm {.8}{-1.1}{1.1}{1.9}{\pgfpoint{0cm}{0cm}}
					\draw[step=.5cm, very thin] (-6,-3) grid (6,3);
					\draw[thick vector] (0,0) --
					node [midway, above left, whitebg] {$v$} (0,1);
					\draw[thick vector] (0,0) --
					node [midway, below left, whitebg] {$w$} (1,0);
					\point["$a$" left] at (2,1);
					\point["$b$" left] at (-1.5,0);
					\point["$c$" left] at (0,-1);
					\point["$d$" left] at (-1.5,.5);
					\point["$e$" left] at (.75,.75);
					\end{scope}
					\point["$0$" left] at (0,0);
					\end{tikzpicture}


				For each of the labeled points, estimate the coefficients x, y such that the linear combination xv + yw is the vector ending at that point.
